{Content
    styleTitle="h2"
    title="Kids' Mobile Devices Monitoring: A Vital Necessity"
    blockBg='light'}

	<p>Today, technology is taking over the world. And when we say 'technology,' for the vast majority of people it means the Internet and web-related products or services. Indeed, one simply cannot imagine a normal life without the World Wide Web. According to Internetlivestats.com, in 2016, the number of Internet users in the world surpassed 3.5 billion, making it almost half of the Earth population. Little less than one-third of them (around 1 billion) are children aged up to 17 years old. Naturally, kids and teens who are less experienced and more trustful than adults are subject to digital dangers above all others. Another crucial thing parents must be aware of is that almost 100% of children who own a smartphone use it to access the Internet. That's why parental mobile monitoring is not a luxury but a necessity vital to ensure your kid's Internet safety.</p>

        <!-- BLOCK STATISTICK -->
        <div class="block-statistick row">

            <div class="item col-s-sm-12 col-xs-sm-12 col-sm-4 col-md-4 col-lg-4">
                <section>
                    <div><strong class="fz50 color-orange">3 in 4</strong></div>
                    <span class="text-uppercase">
                        children who use the Internet experienced one or several of these: online cyberbullying, sexting, seeing inappropriate content, meeting a person previously known online only.
                    </span>
                </section>
            </div>
            <div class="item col-s-sm-12 col-xs-sm-12 col-sm-4 col-md-4 col-lg-4">
                <section>
                    <div><strong class="fz50 color-orange">Almost 70%</strong></div>
                    <span class="text-uppercase">
                        kids admit that they were hiding their online activities from parents. At that, less than half of them say they were looking up content their parents would disapprove of.
                    </span>
                </section>
            </div>
            <div class="item col-s-sm-12 col-xs-sm-12 col-sm-4 col-md-4 col-lg-4">
                <section>
                    <div><strong class="fz50 color-orange">Only 16%</strong></div>
                    <span class="text-uppercase">
                        parents actually use parental controls to watch over and monitor their children’s digital activities. Thanks to this, parents were able to eliminate problems and prevent wrongdoings.
                    </span>
                </section>
            </div>

        </div>
        <!-- END -->

        <p>As you can see, the vast majority of parents tend toward using traditional methods like checking a device manually or taking it away. Instead, they should use appropriate monitoring and safety tools to protect their children from modern perils. Like Pumpic.</p>
		<p>Pumpic is a state-of-the-art phone and tablet legal tracking app. Its features help concerned parents secure their kids’ both online and offline. The app’s functionality provides broad device monitoring options so that parents can go far beyond “Turn it off!” request. Pumpic is available for Android and iOS mobile devices; for the latter ones, you can choose a solution with or without jailbreak (works with iCloud). In any form, this parental app will let you detect and avert possible dangers that threaten your little loved ones.</p>
		<p>Pumpic lets parents rise awareness of who contacts their children and for what purpose, what they do online, or where they go. You can keep track of:</p>
				<ul class="list-images">
				<li><img src="/images/landings/check-icon.png" alt="Check Mark" style="left: -30px;" /><strong>Communications</strong> – calls, SMS, instant messengers;</li>
				<li><img src="/images/landings/check-icon.png" alt="Check Mark" style="left: -30px;" /><strong>Internet activity</strong> – social media, browsing history, bookmarks;</li>
				<li><img src="/images/landings/check-icon.png" alt="Check Mark" style="left: -30px;" /><strong>Location</strong> – current whereabouts, route history, geofences (<i>feature availability restrictions apply</i>);</li>
				<li><img src="/images/landings/check-icon.png" alt="Check Mark" style="left: -30px;" /><strong>Other data</strong> – contacts, calendar, notes, etc.</li>
				</ul>
		<p>Thus, Pumpic enables parents to notice warning signs of a problem (cyberbullying, sexting, online predator attack, etc.) and take necessary steps to shield their kids. Thanks to keeping parents' eyes open, the app helps them prevent or avert troubles or at least minimize their consequences.</p>
